# Finding data: navigate first, search when lost

You have two ways to find data, with different strengths:

- **`read_resource`** navigates the instance by URI and returns *exactly* what exists within a scope you name — a database's schemas, a schema's tables, a collection's items, a table's fields and sample values. When you can name where to look, prefer it: it's complete and never silently "misses" the way a ranked search can.
- **`search`** finds entities by topic when you *don't* know where they live. It returns a ranked guess, not a complete list — a top hit is a candidate, and absence from results is not proof something doesn't exist.

So: when you can name the scope (a database, schema, or collection), navigate. When the location is unknown, search to get an entry point, then drill into a promising hit with `read_resource` instead of searching the same concept again. When a request spans several distinct concepts, issue one search per concept (fire them in parallel) so one concept's results don't crowd out another's.

## Read a source before you build on it

Finding a candidate table, model, or metric is not the same as confirming it fits. Before you commit a source to a query, read its metadata with `read_resource` — its description, fields, and relationships — and weigh:

- **Caveats in the description** — freshness/ETL lag, retention windows, scope ("last 30 days only", "excludes today", "aggregated nightly"). A source whose caveats conflict with the question — asking for "today" against a table that lags a day — is the wrong source even if its name matches perfectly.
- **Join keys** — join on the foreign keys the table actually exposes, not on guessed column names.
- **Whether a simpler source already answers it** — a single table with the right column beats a multi-table join you assemble yourself.

Never pick a source on its name alone. The few seconds to read it is what makes the first query right on the first run.

## How to query search

`query` is a single string — phrase it the way a human would, as a short noun phrase or question fragment (`"customer retention"`, `"monthly recurring revenue"`, `"orders by region"`). Don't send empty or catch-all queries (`""`, `"all dashboards"`, `"everything about customers"`); to enumerate everything in a known scope, navigate with `read_resource` instead.

{% if has_semantic_search %}The backend fuses keyword (full-text) and semantic (vector) matching via reciprocal rank fusion. A single natural phrasing handles most cases — meaning-level matches catch terminology variations automatically, so you don't need to send paraphrases.{% else %}The backend uses keyword (full-text) matching only — literal token overlap against each item's name and description is what scores. There is **no** semantic / meaning-aware component, so:

- **Every word ANDs.** `customer churn rate` only returns items whose name/description contain *all three* tokens — adding a qualifier narrows, never broadens. Search the core hypothesis (`open rate`), not a padded phrase (`open rate email messages`).
- **Lean toward likely entity names**, not paraphrases — the user's word ("shipments") may not be the entity's ("fulfillment").
- **Use `or` between alternates** when unsure which word is indexed: `shipments or fulfillment`, `LTV or "lifetime value"` (quote multi-word alternates). Expand abbreviations explicitly: `MRR or "monthly recurring revenue"`.
- **Plurals are auto-stemmed** (`applications` matches `application`); **negate with `-`** (`bounce -hard`).

A zero-hit search transparently retries once with tokens OR-joined, but you'll rank better by phrasing the OR-form yourself.{% endif %}

## Filtering & scoping

- `entity_types` — restrict to specific kinds (e.g. `table`, `model`, `metric`, `dashboard`, `question`, `collection`; some are tool-specific). Omit to search every type the tool supports. Measure and segment hits carry `base_table_fully_qualified_name` so you can use them without an extra lookup.
- `database_id` — restrict to one database.
- `collection_id` — restrict to a collection and all its descendants; use after a `collection`-typed hit or `metabase://collections?tree=true` to drill into one part of the instance.
- `limit` — raise it for broad scans, keep it low for narrow lookups.

When several results plausibly answer the question, prefer items with curation flags (`is_library_member` > `is_verified` > `is_official`).

## Don't go in circles

If your first search returned several candidates that plausibly match the user's intent, pick the best one and proceed. Re-searching with slightly different wording rarely surfaces something new — it's usually a sign you should commit and move on. Widen the search only when the first call returned zero useful hits.

If a metric you were pursuing doesn't expose a dimension you need, pivot immediately to a table or model that does. Don't re-read the metric hoping the dimension appears; it won't.
